body:
Not sure if I read the code correctly... but I think that if an application has set `CURLOPT_NOSIGNAL` to 1, curl 8.9.1 (without this bugfix) will replace the application's signal handler for `SIGPIPE`, and not restore it later.

`sigpipe_apply()` will call `sigpipe_restore()`, and there this is called:
```
sigaction(SIGPIPE, &ig->old_pipe_act, NULL);
```

`ig` has been initialized to zeroes, so it does not contain a valid signal handler, but this test program shows that the previous signal handler gets replaced:
```
#include <signal.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <unistd.h>

int main()
{
  struct sigaction x;
  memset(&x, '\0', sizeof(x));

  signal(SIGPIPE, SIG_IGN);
  sigaction(SIGPIPE, &x, NULL);

  usleep(100000000);

  return 0;
}
```

If you send this program a `SIGPIPE`, it will quit (at least on Linux).

@bagder I think that this is quite a serious regression, and it has been introduced in a curl bugfix release (8.9.1), so another bugfix release (8.9.2) is probably a good idea...
